POP Operation (Stack)
1. What is Pop?

Imagine a stack of plates.

Top
 ↓
Plate 3
Plate 2
Plate 1

If someone asks you to remove a plate, which plate can you remove?

✅ Only the top plate.

You cannot remove Plate 2 or Plate 1 directly.

This operation is called POP.

Definition:

Pop removes and returns the top-most element from the stack.

Since a stack follows LIFO (Last In, First Out), the last inserted element is always removed first.

2. Syntax in Java
stack.pop();

Example

Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();

stack.push(10);
stack.push(20);
stack.push(30);

stack.pop();
3. Visualization

Initially

Top
 ↓
30
20
10

Now perform

stack.pop();

The top element (30) is removed.

After Pop

Top
 ↓
20
10

Removed Element

30
4. Step-by-Step Working

Suppose the stack contains

Top
 ↓
50
40
30
20
10
Step 1

Call

stack.pop();
Step 2

Stack looks at the top element.

50
Step 3

Removes it.

Step 4

Returns the removed value.

50

Final Stack

Top
 ↓
40
30
20
10
5. Example Program
import java.util.Stack;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();

        stack.push(10);
        stack.push(20);
        stack.push(30);

        System.out.println("Before Pop : " + stack);

        int removed = stack.pop();

        System.out.println("Removed Element : " + removed);

        System.out.println("After Pop : " + stack);
    }
}
Output
Before Pop : [10, 20, 30]

Removed Element : 30

After Pop : [10, 20]
6. What Does pop() Return?

Many beginners think Pop only removes an element.

Actually it does two things.

1. Removes the top element
Top
 ↓
30
20
10

↓

Top
 ↓
20
10
2. Returns the removed element
30

Example

int x = stack.pop();

System.out.println(x);

Output

30
7. Time Complexity
Operation	Time Complexity
Pop	O(1)

Why?

Because the stack always knows where the top element is.

It doesn't need to search.

It simply removes the top element.

8. What Happens Internally?

Suppose the stack is

Top
 ↓
30
20
10

Internally

top = 2

because 30 is at index 2.

When Pop happens

Return stack[top]

top--

Now

top = 1

New Stack

Top
 ↓
20
10

Only the top pointer moves one position down.

9. Pop in Array Implementation

Suppose

Index

0   1   2
---------
10  20  30

top = 2

Pop

Return 30

top = top - 1

Now

Index

0   1   2
---------
10  20  30

top = 1

Notice

The value 30 may still exist in memory, but since top = 1, the stack ignores it.

Logically the stack is

20
10
10. Pop in Linked List Implementation

Suppose

Head (Top)

↓

30 → 20 → 10 → null

Pop

Move the head to the next node.

head = head.next;

Now

Head

↓

20 → 10 → null

Node 30 is removed.

11. Underflow

What if the stack is empty?

Top

↓

Empty

Now

stack.pop();

There is nothing to remove.

This situation is called

Stack Underflow

In Java

EmptyStackException

is thrown.

12. Safe Way

Instead of directly writing

stack.pop();

Always check

if(!stack.isEmpty())
{
    stack.pop();
}

This prevents an exception.

